var_pretty: Total Population
national_summary_text: The U.S. Census Bureau sample for reporting most disability data is the civilian noninstitutional population. This includes all people who live in the community. This does not include residents of institutions (e.g., penal and mental facilities, homes for the aged) nor active duty in the Armed Forces.

var_pretty: % People with Disability
national_summary_text: According to the U.S. Census Bureau, a person is considered to have a disability if they report one of six disability types (hearing, vision, cognitive, ambulatory, self-care, or independent living).

var_pretty: % People without Disability
national_summary_text: According to the U.S. Census Bureau, a person is considered to have a disability if they do not report one of six disability types (hearing, vision, cognitive, ambulatory, self-care, or independent living).

var_pretty: # People with Disability
# People without Disability
Type: % Hearing Disability
national_summary_text: According to the U.S. Census Bureau, a hearing disability is defined as being deaf or having serious difficulty hearing.

var_pretty: Type: % Vision Disability
national_summary_text: According to the U.S. Census Bureau, a vision disability is defined as being blind or having serious difficulty seeing, even when wearing glasses

var_pretty: Type: % Cognitive Disability
national_summary_text: According to the U.S. Census Bureau, a cognitive disability is defined as having difficulty remembering, concentrating, or making decisions because of a physical, mental, or emotional problem.

var_pretty: Type: % Mobility Disability
national_summary_text: According to the U.S. Census Bureau, a mobility or ambulatory disability is defined as having serious difficulty walking or climbing stairs.

var_pretty: Type: % Self Care Disability
national_summary_text: According to the U.S. Census Bureau, a self-care disability is defined as having difficulty bathing or dressing.

var_pretty: Type: % Independent Living Disability
national_summary_text: According to the U.S. Census Bureau, an independent living disability is defined as having difficulty doing errands alone such as visiting a doctor's office or shopping because of a physical, mental, or emotional problem.

Race & Ethnicity: % White with Disability
national_summary_text: According to the U.S. Census Bureau, white is defined as a person having origins in any of the original peoples of Europe, the Middle East, or North Africa.

var_pretty: Race & Ethnicity: % Black or African American with Disability
national_dropdown_label: Race & Ethnicity: Black or African American
national_summary_text: According to the U.S. Census Bureau, Black or African American is defined as a person having origins in any of the Black racial groups of Africa.

var_pretty: Race & Ethnicity: % Hispanic with Disability
national_summary_text: According to the U.S. Census Bureau, Hispanic or Latino is defined as a person of Cuban, Mexican, Puerto Rican, South or Central American, or other Spanish culture or origin regardless of race.

var_pretty: Race & Ethnicity: % Asian with Disability
national_summary_text: According to the U.S. Census Bureau, Asian is defined as a person with origins in of any of the original peoples of the Far East, Southeast Asia, or the Indian subcontinent including, for example, Cambodia, China, India, Japan, Korea, Malaysia, Pakistan, the Philippine Islands, Thailand, and Vietnam.

var_pretty: Race & Ethnicity: % Some other race with Disability
national_summary_text: According to the U.S. Census Bureau, other races include American Indian or Alaska Native with origins in any of the original peoples of North and South America (including Central America) and who maintains tribal affiliation or community attachment, and Native Hawaiian or Other Pacific Islander with origins in any of the original peoples of Hawaii, Guam, Samoa, or other Pacific Islands.

national_summary_text: According to the U.S. Census Bureau, two or more races is defined as more than one race category.

Employment: % Not in Labor Force with Disability
national_summary_text: According to the U.S. Census, people who are not in labor force includes all people 16 years old and over who have no job and who are not looking for one. People not in the labor force include students, housewives, retired workers, seasonal workers interviewed in an off season who were not looking for work, institutionalized people, and people doing only incidental unpaid family work (less than 15 hours/week).
